---
import "../styles/global.css";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";

const ssrnUrl =
  "https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=5984574";
---

<!doctype html>

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />

    <meta
      name="viewport"
      content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"
    />

    <title>
      Power, Tolerance and Legitimacy | Minimal Tolerance
    </title>

    <meta
      name="description"
      content="Power, Tolerance and Legitimacy by Federico Rodrigo examines coercion, political authority and the limits of state power."
    />

    <link
      rel="canonical"
      href="https://minimaltolerance.com/book"
    />
  </head>

  <body>

    <Header />

    <main>

      <section class="page-hero">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE BOOK
          </p>

          <h1>
            Power, Tolerance and Legitimacy
          </h1>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="statement">

        <blockquote>
          The question is not whether coercive power is legitimate.
The question is how much of it can be tolerated
        </blockquote>

      </section>

      <section class="book">

        <div class="container">

          <div class="book-grid">

            <div>

              <img
                src="/images/book-cover.jpg"
                alt="Cover of Power, Tolerance and Legitimacy by Federico Rodrigo"
              />

            </div>

            <div>

              <p class="eyebrow">
                ABOUT THE BOOK
              </p>

              <h2>
                A Theory of Power and Legitimacy
              </h2>

              <p>
                Power, Tolerance and Legitimacy begins from the
                argument that the State possesses no intrinsic moral
                legitimacy and remains constrained by structural
                informational, economic and institutional limitations.
              </p>

              <p>
                Coercion therefore requires justification rather than
                presumption. The book develops the moral and functional
                arguments that culminate in the Theory of Minimal
                Tolerance.
              </p>

              <p>
                The result is a framework for identifying the
                exceptionally narrow circumstances under which state
                coercion may be tolerated without being morally
                legitimized.
              </p>

            </div>

          </div>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            STRUCTURE
          </p>

          <h2>
            Three Acts
          </h2>

          <p>
            The first act examines the moral and economic problems
            surrounding political coercion and develops the Theory
            of Minimal Tolerance.
          </p>

          <p>
            The second tests the theory against its strongest
            objections and examines how narrow exceptions become
            instruments for the expansion of power.
          </p>

          <p>
            The third turns to bureaucracy, institutional
            self-limitation and the conditions required for a
            tolerable political order.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="ssrn">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            FOUNDATIONAL PAPER
          </p>

          <h2>
            Read the SSRN Paper
          </h2>

          <p>
            The original paper presents the formal theorem and
            provides the theoretical foundation for the book.
          </p>

          <a
            href={ssrnUrl}
            class="primary"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >
            Open on SSRN
          </a>

        </div>

      </section>

    </main>

    <Footer />

  </body>
</html>
